case 1: Heta stores her favorite recipes on github. Jose and Jian would like to start from Heta's recipes, and collaborate on new versions based on their taste preferences.¶

  • git clone remote repository to your computer
  • good for starting seperate collaborations based on existing github repos
  • issue: no history of who made recipe repo 
## reset your local repo remote origin to the url copied
git remote set-url origin https://github.com/___/___.git
git status
git push
## confirm files added to your github account

#### alternatively: 
- if you wanted to connect a folder on your computer to your github account, use this command to set remote: 
git remote add origin https://github.com/___/___.git
git remote -v # sets origin

case 2: similar to case 1, but now using the github 'fork' method to copy the original recipes repo to her github account¶

  • git fork __ (skips cloning to local computer step)
  • good for maintaining collaboration with original author with suggestions
  • issue: github tracks who forks original repo, and to make significant changes to content of repo, you will need to first clone data to your computer.

3 main git commands:¶

git add __

git commit -m "..."

git push

[1] git clone repository on BackusLab account¶

# to download cheatsheet to local computer
git clone ____ (url of remote)

[2] on your computer, login to github and 'Fork' BackusLab/testme to your personal account¶

## on your account, copy url of forked repo
# on computer in terminal or in desktop app: 
git clone https://github.com/youraccount/testme.git
cd testme
git status # clean branch
touch change.txt # create new file
git status # untracked file
git add . # add all files
git status # shows changes staged for commit step
git commit -m "" # add message
git push
## confirm files added to your github account

[3] merge conflict example¶

  • make edits to file locally
  • commit changes
  • on github: create new file in repo
  • on computer: push staged changes to remote
  • dont panic

WARNING: google all error messages before force overriding a merge conflict

In [41]:
largepic("merge_screenshot.png")

resolve merge conflict:¶

git pull # integrate remote changes
## type 'i' to insert message in git prompt
## then type 'ESC' ':wq' saves message or ':q' to escape no save

# now you should be able to stage local change and push to remote
git add . 
git commit -m "that wasn't so bad after all"
git push

[3] create new Rstudio project from forked repo¶

  • fork BackusLab/Rstudio_github repo to your account
  • in your forked repo, copy url (https instead of ssh option)
  • in Rstudio, create new project, select option to create from github
  • enter copied url of remote repo

under git tab in Rstudio¶

  • add the name or file '.Rproj' to the .gitignore file
  • save changes to file
  • git commit '.gitignore' by checking box 'staged' and clicking 'commit'
  • add commit message, click commit
  • push to your remote account, check if changes reflected on account

Summary of git commands :¶

1. Introduction to Version Control Systems¶

$ git init

2. The .git Folder¶

$ ls -al

3. Creating Files in the Repository¶

$ echo -e 'if name == "main":\n print(

4. Checking File Status¶

$ git add README.md

5. Configuring Identity in Git¶

$ git config --global user.name "MFP"

6. Committing Changes¶

$ git commit -m "Initial commit. Added script.py

7. Viewing File Differences¶

$ git status

8. Making a Second Commit¶

$ git commit -m "added random function "

9. Viewing Commit Differences¶

$ git log --stat
